T1  - Should SME exposures be treated as retail or corporate exposures? A comparative analysis of default probabilities and asset correlations in French and German SMEs
AU  - Dietsch, Michel
AU  - Petey, Joël
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 28
IS  - 4
SP  - 773
EP  - 788
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/04/01/
T2  - Retail Credit Risk Management and Measurement
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbankfin.2003.10.006
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426603001997
KW  - Credit risk
KW  - Small and medium enterprises
KW  - Bank capital regulation
AB  - We use a one-factor credit risk model to provide new estimates of stationary default probabilities and asset correlations in two large samples of French and German Small and Medium-sized Enterprises. Results show that, on average, SMEs are riskier than large businesses; and the asset correlations in the SME population are very weak (1–3% on average) and decrease with size. On average, the relationship between PDs and asset correlations is not negative, as assumed by Basel II, but positive, especially at the industry level, in the two countries. It is also possible to distinguish different segments inside the SMEs’ population: at least between very small and small SMEs and large SMEs.
